[1] Namibia
Date: 21 Jun 2006
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: TerraNet [edited]
<http://www.terra.net.lb/wp/Articles/DesktopArticle.aspx?ArticleID=291673&ChannelId=19>

Namibia says polio cases rise sharply
-------------------------------------------
Namibia's 1st outbreak of polio in more than a decade has killed 15,
and the number of cases has risen sharply to 96, the health minister
said on the eve of a mass vaccination campaign.
"I am saddened to report that the number has risen to 96 polio
cases," Richard Kamwi told parliament, adding: "The death cases from
the polio outbreak [have] risen to 15 by today [21 Jun 2006]."
Namibia will on Wednesday [21 Jun 2006] launch a mass vaccination
program countrywide to inoculate its 2-million population over a
period of 3 days with vaccines supplied by the UN children's agency UNICEF.
Experts from the World Health Organization are in Namibia to help
stamp out the disease that can damage the nervous system and cause paralysis.
The 1st case was detected on [6 May 2006]; tests conducted in South
Africa [confirmed] that it was polio.
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo.nart@terra.es>
